# never use toThrow when testing reducer errors

The most common testing mistake with Powerhouse reducers:

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — this will always pass (no error is thrown to the caller)
expect(() => reducer(document, setName({ name: "invalid" }))).toThrow();

// ✅ CORRECT — check the operation's error property
const updated = reducer(document, setName({ name: "invalid" }));
expect(updated.operations.global[0].error).toBe("Name is not allowed");
expect(updated.state.global.name).toBe(initialState); // state unchanged
```

Since [[operation errors are recorded on operations not thrown to callers]], the error is captured silently on the operation object. The reducer call itself never throws — it always returns a document. The error lives in `operations.global[N].error`.

Since [[operation error index must match the number of prior dispatches]], make sure you check the right index.

